in theory when the value of m =2, L=1, and k = 4 is used the residual should become zero with the corresponding value of Pz = 0.045 = ΔG_ij
i.e. interface energy, σ = (1/3) sqrt(2mk)
driving force for an interface Pd = σ/R # here R is the radius of curvature
based on this if R = 30 , σ = 1.3333 (based on the values of m and k mentioned above)
Pd = 0.04444
that means if Pz = 0.045 which is more than Pd, the interface should not move at all.
That is the driving foce (1st and third term in above equation) becomes equal to the pinning force (second term in above equation).
That is in theory. But when I am solving the PDE in MOOSE, even with Pz=1 the residual never becomes zero.
This should not happen.
The way I am writing these terms in moose kernel is  as follows
  Real SumEtaj = 0.0;
  Real SumEtaj_G = 0.0;
  for (unsigned int i = 0; i < _op_num; ++i)
  {
    SumEtaj += (*_vals[i])[_qp] * (*_vals[i])[_qp];
    SumEtaj_G += (*_vals[i])[_qp];
  }

  Real g = _g[_qp];
  Real total = (_test[_i][_qp] * _mu[_qp] *
                (_u[_qp] * _u[_qp] * _u[_qp] - _u[_qp] + 3 * _u[_qp] * SumEtaj)) +
               (_grad_u[_qp] * _kappa[_qp] * _grad_test[_i][_qp]); //1st and 3rd term in above equation

  Real friction = _test[_i][_qp] * 3 * g * _u[_qp] * SumEtaj_G; //second term in above equation, Pz = g

The set of equations are correct that means the only possible explanation is that moose is not able to calculate the interpolation function (second term) value correctly.
Unless you think the equation is wrongly written in the kernel.
The same equation and corresponding values of constants were used in analytical model and an FDM model. Both these models shows the desired results except in moose.

I remember asking this question in my very early queries long time ago.

As you can see the way MOOSE implemented this equation has negative sign to the third term of equation, but if you look at the grain growth action kernel, there is no negative sign in ACInterface.
GrainGrowthAction = TimeDerivative + ACGrGrPoly + ACInterface
